+# Why CVE-2005-2541 Is Usually Non-Actionable for Stock GNU `tar` on Debian
+
+## Overview: What Is the Issue with `tar`?
+
+**GNU `tar`** is the standard archiving utility on many Linux systems. Debian ships it as the **`tar`** source package. CVE-2005-2541 is an old entry about **`tar`** extracting **setuid/setgid** (and related permission bits) and whether **`tar` warns** clearly enough before restoring privileged modes. NVD text can read severely if archives are handled **carelessly** (for example extracting **untrusted** tarballs as **root**).
+
+In audits, scanners often flag this CVE from **installed `tar` version metadata**, without reflecting **Debian’s classification** or **normal safe usage**.
+
+---
+
+## Why This CVE Is Often Not Fixable via a “tar Security Patch” in the Usual Sense
+
+Security scanners (Trivy, Grype, Snyk, etc.) may report CVE-2005-2541 because:
+
+- Package databases match **old CVE records** to current **`tar`** versions
+- CVE text can assume **worst-case operator behaviour**
+- Scanner output rarely surfaces **Debian urgency** or **maintainer intent**
+
+**Vendor / distro posture:**
+
+- On NVD, Red Hat’s **vendor statement** describes **documented, expected behaviour** of `tar` (see [NVD – CVE-2005-2541](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2005-2541), Vendor Statements).
+- Debian’s tracker marks the issue **unimportant** with **(unfixed)** and notes **intended behaviour** for an archiving tool (appropriate **flags**, e.g. `-p`, and operator judgement — see [Debian tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2005-2541) **Notes**).
+
+---
+
+## False positive vs. exception (wording)
+
+- **Strict false positive:** Often means the scanner is wrong about the **component or version**. Here the CVE ID commonly **does** match real **`tar`** packages, so “FP” in that narrow sense is **debatable**.
+- **Practical stance:** Debian **unimportant** + **intended behaviour** supports documenting this as **non-actionable** / **exception** / **accepted risk** with tracker citations, or as **“FP for remediation”** only if your internal policy defines FP that way.
+
+---
+
+# CVE Breakdown
+
+CVE-2005-2541 concerns **`tar`** behaviour around **setuid/setgid** restoration and warnings. Debian does **not** treat it like a typical “ship a security update to close the CVE” item for **`tar`** in the tracker sense shown for this entry.
+
+---
+
+## CVE-2005-2541 — `tar` and setuid/setgid extraction
+
+- **Component:** GNU `tar` (Debian **source package `tar`**)
+- **Issue class:** Warnings / behaviour around restoring privileged file modes from archives
+- **Debian tracker:** **unimportant**, **(unfixed)** — see [Debian tracker](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2005-2541), [bug #328228](https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=328228)
+
+### Why scanners still flag it
+
+Tools match **installed `tar`** to 2005 CVE metadata. They rarely encode **unimportant** classification or “expected tool behaviour” notes from the distribution.
+
+### Operational guidance
+
+- Do **not** extract **untrusted** archives as **root**
+- Follow **`tar(1)`** and your distribution’s guidance for permission / preserve semantics
+
+---
+
+## Summary
+
+- CVE-2005-2541 is about **`tar`** archive handling and **privileged mode** restoration, not a modern “patch `tar` source to fix memory corruption” style issue in Debian’s tracker view for this row
+- Debian lists it as **unimportant** / **intended behaviour** for an archiving utility
+- Mitigation is **operational**: trusted archives only, appropriate flags, least privilege
+
+**Recommendation:** For typical images where **untrusted tarballs are not extracted as root**, document as **non-impactful** and cite the **Debian tracker**. Prefer **exception / non-actionable** over a bare **false positive** unless your policy defines FP broadly.
+
+---
+
+## References
+
+- [Debian Security Tracker – CVE-2005-2541](https://security-tracker.debian.org/tracker/CVE-2005-2541)
+- [NVD – CVE-2005-2541](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2005-2541)
